'''''Verbascum thapsus''''' ('''Common''' or '''Great Mullein''') is a species of [[mullein]], native to [[Europe]], northern [[Africa]] and [[Asia]], and introduced in the [[Americas]] and [[Australia]]. 

Common mullein is a hairy [[biennial plant]] that can grow up to 2&nbsp;meters. Its small yellow flowers are densely grouped on the stem, which bolts from a large rosette of leaves. It grows in a wide variety of habitats, but favors well-lit disturbed soils, where it can grow suddenly thanks to its long-lived seeds. Common Mullein is a common weedy plant that spreads by way of its large seed production, but rarely is an aggressively invasive species since its seed require open ground to [[germination|germinate]]. This species of mullein is a very minor problem for most agricultural crops since it is not a very competitive plant, being intolerant of shade from other plants and unable to survive tilling. However, it hosts many insects, such as the [[tarnished plant bug]], that can be harmful to other plants. Although individuals are easy to destroy by hand, populations are difficult to eliminate permanently since Common mullein, with its heavy seed production, has seeds that persist in the [[soil seed bank]] for many years, and may reappear when the ground is disturbed. 

''V. thapsus'' is widely used as an herbal remedy with [[emollient]] and [[astringent]] properties. It is especially recommended for coughs and related problems, but also used in [[topical]] applications against a variety of skin problems. The plant was also used to make [[dye]]s and [[torch]]es.

==Description==

[[Image:Starr 040723 0260 verbascum thapsus.jpg|right|thumb|A stemless rosette in [[Hawaii]]]]
[[Image:Starr 040723 0267 verbascum thapsus.jpg|right|thumb|A closeup of the flowers]]

Common Mullein is a [[dicotyledon]]ous biennial that produces a [[rosette (botany)|rosette]] of  leaves in its first year of growth.<ref name="remaley"/><ref name="davis"/> The leaves are large up to  50 cm long and lay flat over the ground and are covered with wholly, silver-gray colored hairs.  The second year plants normally produce a single unbranched stem 1–2&nbsp;m tall with some plants  reportedly having stems reaching up to and exceeding 3&nbsp;m (10&nbsp;ft) tall.<ref>[http://www.purplesage.org.uk/profiles/mullein.htm Purple Sage Herbs: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on [[December 29]] [[2006]].</ref><ref>{{cite web| last=Jacobson| first=Arthur Lee| title=Mullein| url=http://www.arthurleej.com/a-mullein.html| work=The Weed of the Month| publisher=arthurleej.com| month=January| year=1992| accessdate=2007-03-07}}</ref> The tall pole-like stems end in a dense [[raceme|spike]] of flowers,<ref name="remaley"/> that can occupy up to half the stem length.  All parts of the plants are covered with star-shaped [[trichome]]s.<ref name="china">{{Cite web|title=Verbascum thapsus|url=http://www.efloras.org/florataxon.aspx?flora_id=2&taxon_id=200021301|work=Flora of China|publisher=eFloras.org|accessdate=2006-11-29}}</ref><ref name="jepson">{{cite web|last=Wetherwax|first=M.| year=1993|title=Verbascum thapsus L. |url=http://ucjeps.berkeley.edu/cgi-bin/get_JM_treatment.pl?7177,7595,7598 |work=Jepson Manual online|publisher=[[University of California at Berkeley]]|accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref>

On blooming plants the leaves are alternately arranged up the stem. The leaves are thick and [[decurrent]], with much variation especially between the upper and lower leaves on the stem, with leaf shape ranging from between [[leaf shape|oblong to oblanceolate]] and ranging in size up to 14&nbsp;cm across and 50&nbsp;cm long (5&nbsp;inches wide and 19&nbsp;inches long).<ref name="huxley">Huxley, A., ed. (1992). ''New RHS Dictionary of Gardening''. Macmillan. ISBN 0-333-47494-5</ref><ref name="remaley"/> They become smaller as they progress up the stem,<ref name="davis"/><ref name="remaley"/> and less strongly decurrent as they progress lower down the stem.<ref name="FlEu">{{cite encyclopedia | last = Ferguson | first = Ian Keith | editor = Tutin, Thomas Gaskell ''et als.'' | encyclopedia = Flora Europaea | title = V. thapsus | year = 1972 | publisher = Cambridge University Press | volume = Volume 3: Diapensiaceae to Myoporaceae | location = Cambridge | id = ISBN 0-521-08489-X | pages = p. 211}}</ref> The flowering stem is solid and nearly an inch (2.5&nbsp;cm) across and sometimes [[branch]]ed just below the [[inflorescence]],<ref name="davis"/> usually when damaged.<ref name="Hoshovsky">{{cite web|first=Marc C.|last= Hoshovsky|title=Element Stewardship Abstract for Verbascum thapsus|url=http://tncweeds.ucdavis.edu/esadocs/documnts/verbtha.pdf| month=August |year=2001 |publisher= The Global Invasive Species Initiative|accessdate=2006-11-29}}</ref> After flowering and seed release the stem and fruits usually persist in winter<ref name="illinois"/> after drying into hard, stiff structures topped with densely packed, ovoid shaped, dry seed capsules. The dried stems are most often a dark brownish color and often persist standing until the next spring or even into the next summer. The plants produce a shallow [[taproot]].<ref name="remaley"/>

Flowers are pentamerous with five [[stamen]] that are fused to the petals and a 5-lobed [[calyx tube]] and a 5-petaled [[corolla]], the latter bright yellow and an inch or less wide.  The flowers are almost [[sessile]], with very short [[pedicel (botany)|pedicel]]s (2&nbsp;mm, 0.08&nbsp;in). The five stamens are of two types, with the three upper stamens being shorter, with filaments covered by yellow or whitish hairs, and having smaller [[anther]]s, while the lower two stamens have [[glabrous]] filaments and larger anthers.<ref name="jepson"/>{{ref label|Stamens|A|}} The plant produces small ovoid (6&nbsp;mm, 0.24&nbsp;in) [[capsule (fruit)|capsule]]s that split open by way of two valves, each capsule containing large numbers of minute brown [[seed]]s less than a millimetre (0.04&nbsp;in)<ref name="davis"/> in size, with longitudinal ridges.  Sometimes a white-flowered form called, f. ''candicans'' occurs.<ref name="pennel"/> Plants bloom for a month and a half in mid- to late summer,<ref name="jepson"/><ref name="remaley"/> with flowering starting at the bottom of the spike and progressing up the spike with each flower open for part of a day with only a few flowers open at the same time produced around the stem.<ref name="illinois"/>

==Taxonomy and nomenclature==
[[Image:Vthapsus sheet.JPG|thumb|right|The dried type specimen (LINN 242.1) of ''Verbascum thapsus''.]]
For the purpose of [[botanical nomenclature]], the species was first described by [[Carolus Linnaeus]] in his 1753 ''[[Species Plantarum]]''. The [[specific epithet]] ''thapsus'' had been first used by [[Theophrastus]] (as ''θάψος'', "thapsos")<ref name="carnoy"/> for an unspecified herb from the [[Ancient Greece|Ancient Greek]] settlement of Thapsos, near modern [[Syracuse, Sicily|Syracuse]], [[Sicily]],<ref>{{sv icon}} [http://linnaeus.nrm.se/flora/di/scrophularia/verba/verbtha.html Den virtuella Floran: ''Verbascum thapsus''], retrieved on [[December 29]] [[2006]].</ref><ref name="carnoy">{{fr icon}}{{cite book| last=Carnoy| first=A. |title=Dictionnaire étymologique des noms grecs de plantes| year=1959|location=Louvain| publisher= Publications Universitaires| oclc=3284108}}</ref> though it is often assimilated to the ancient [[Tunisia]]n city of [[Thapsus]].<ref>{{Cite web|last=Charters|first=Michael L.|title=Plant name: T| work= California Plant Names: Latin and Greek Meanings and Derivations| url=http://www.calflora.net/botanicalnames/pageT.html|publisher=Calflora.net| accessdate=2006-12-06}}</ref> Within ''[[Verbascum]]'', it classified under section ''Bothrosperma'' subsect. ''Fasciculata''.<!--reference temporary, details to come from Murbeck (1933)--><ref>{{cite journal|last=Lersten|first=Nels R.| coauthor=John D. Curtis|title=Anatomy and Distribution of Foliar Idioblasts in Scrophularia and Verbascum (Scrophulariaceae)| month=December| year=1997| volume=84|issue=12| pages=1638-1645| doi=10.2307/2446461}}</ref>

At the time, no [[type specimen]] was specified, as the practice only appeared later, in the 19th century. When a lectotype (type designed amongst original material) was designated, it was assigned to specimen 242.1 of Linnaeus' herbarium, the only ''V. thapsus'' specimen. The species had previously been designated as [[type species]] for ''Verbascum''.<ref>{{cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus''| url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/jdsml/research-curation/projects/linnaean-typification/detail.dsml?ID=925400| work=Linnaean Plant Name Typification Project| publisher=Natural History Museum| accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref> European plants exhibit much more [[phenotype|phenotypical]] variation than the American ones,<ref name="BoCW"/> which has lead to the plant acquiring many [[synonymy|synonyms]] over the years.<ref>{{Cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus'' synonymy| url=http://www.northernontarioflora.ca/chklst.cfm?speciesid=1004482| publisher=Northern Ontario Plant Database|accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus'': synonyms| url=http://www.plantatlas.usf.edu/synonyms.asp?plantID=1757| work=Atlas of Florida vascular Plants | publisher=Institute for Systematic Botany |accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref>

Type - specimen(s)
* Lectotype: (LINN-242.1). Designated by L. H. Cramer, in Dassanayake & Fosberg, ''A Revised Handbook to the Flora of Ceylon'' 3: 389 (1981)<ref>{{Cite web| title=''Verbascum thapsus'': citation| url=http://www.plantatlas.usf.edu/details.asp?plantID=1757| work=Atlas of Florida vascular Plants | publisher=Institute for Systematic Botany |accessdate=2007-05-16}}</ref>

===Subspecies and hybrids===

There are three [[subspecies]]:
*''V. thapsus'' subsp. ''thapsus''; type, widespread.
*''V. thapsus'' subsp. ''crassifolium'' (Lam.) Murb.; Mediterranean region and to 2000 metres in southwestern Austria.<ref name=schmeil/> (syn. subsp. ''montanum'' (Scrad.) Bonnier & Layens)
*''V. thapsus'' subsp. ''giganteum'' (Willk.) Nyman; Spain, endemic.
In all subspecies but the type, the lower stamens are also pilose (having scattered straight long soft hairs).<ref>{{es icon}} {{cite web|title=''Verbascum thapsus'' L. subsp. ''montanum'' (Schrad.) Bonnier et layens |url=http://herbarivirtual.uib.es/cas-med/especie/4440.html| publisher=Universitat de les Illes Balears| work=Herbario Virtual del Mediterráneo Occidental| accessdate=2007-05-12}}</ref> In subsp. ''crassifolium'', the hairiness is less dense and often absent from the upper part of the anthers, and lower leaves are hardly decurrent and have longer petioles<ref name=schmeil>{{cite book| last =Schmeil| first =Otto| authorlink =| coauthors =Fitschen, Jost; Seybold, Siegmund| title =Flora von Deutschland, 93. Auflage| publisher =Quelle & Meyer Verlag| date =2006| location =Wiebelsheim| pages =496| url =| doi =| isbn =3-494-01413-2 }}</ref>, whereas in subsp. ''giganteum'', the hairs are densely white tomentose, and lower leaves strongly decurrent. Subsp. ''crassifolium'' also differs from the type in having slightly larger flowers, which measure 15 to 30 mm wide, whereas in the type they are 12 to 20 mm in diameter.<ref name=schmeil/> Both subspecies ''giganteum'' and ''crassifolium'' were originally described as species.<ref name="FlEu"/> Other described subspecies that have not been widely accepted include subspp. ''martinezii'' (Valdés) A.Galán and J.A.V.Orellana (=''V. giganteum'' subsp. ''martinezii'' Valdés), ''litigiosum'' (=''V. litigiosum'' Samp.)<ref>{{cite journal| last=Galán de Mera| first=Antonio| coauthor=José Alfredo Vicente
Orellana|title=Dos nuevas combinaciones en ''Verbascum'' subsect. ''fasciculata'' Murbeck (Scrophulariaceae) del sudoeste de la Península Ibérica: ''Verbascum thapsus'' subsp. ''litigiosum'' (Samp.), comb. & stat. nov. y ''Verbascum thapsus'' subsp. ''martinezii'' (Valdés), comb. nov.| Anales del Jardín Botánico de Madrid|year=1995|volume=53|issue=2|pages=261-262| url=http://www.rjb.csic.es/pdfs/Anales_53(2)_245_270.pdf| accessdate=2007-05-14}}</ref> and  ''langei''.

